>>114058963
1) It didn't fit into traditional European classical harmonic theory. Prior to the late 18th century classical music was very strict in regards to how chords could be built and voiced, and what their functions were (ie. how they could be placed in a progression and how their tensions had to be resolved). Beginning with the Romantic period, composers sought more expressive freedom within the structures and forms of classical, and began a process of undermining and challenging the "rules" composers, theorists and critics historically used to analyse and compose. Schoenberg comes very late in this story, and arguably ended this period of experimentation with serialism.
2) Basically none when it comes to 12TET music. There are some musicians that experiment with microtonality to produce new chords, but the number of people who can really hear and distinguish those kinds of chords is relatively small. Check out Jacob Collier if you're interested in that, though I can't say I'm a huge fan.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114059341
>learn triads bro

I will try and explain why that is a fool's errand as opposed to >>114059383

There are 4 primary triads . Excluding one which is a bit special, the remaining three each have 2 unique inversions. That means 10 unique tone arrangements must that must be remembered.

On a piano and even other string instruments that would not be that much of a feat especially if you properly utilize scale degrees to remember them. But, on guitar it is a huge pain.

Standard tuning is messy and multiplies the amount of patterns by 3 (assuming 3 adjacent strings are used to play the harmonic triad). Worse than that, many of these duplicate patterns produced by the tuning irregularity are actually tonally different, but identical in shape on given string sets, making them even harder to remember and prone to causing confusion.

Example of this phenomena below.

Given a single fingering, we produce the following completely different triad arrangements across the strings:

3-2-1-x-x-x = augmented triad
x-3-2-1-x-x = augmented triad (same as above)
x-x-3-2-1-x = major triad
x-x-x-3-2-1 = minor triad

This is one of the reasons why the guitar is a terrible instrument to learn music theory on. It is difficult to intuitively grasp interval relations because they vary across strings.

Stick to the cowboy chords and go for typical play styles that make use of them. Don't fall for memes that will be useless because even if you somehow drill your brain with these triads you will still lack contextual understanding on how to use them and they sound bland to boot.

>I know I`m way late to the party. But what the hell did really happen between Waters and Gilmore? Can't they see their at their best together?

Firstly, why the absolute fuck have you used a grave accent instead of a fucking apostrophe for "I'm"?

Secondly,
>their... their
You absolute fucking mongoloid. For this I can't forgive you; even an ESL should see at a glance that it's wrong. Why is it wrong? Answer: because you've repeated the same fucking word. I had to reread your sentence because it made no sense. Then I realised it wasn't me who's retarded, but you.

Thirdly: Waters is a gay boomer who's hell-bent on sticking the middle finger to hegemonic power structures, including Israel and, recently, the US (for the current developments in Ukraine), which is hilarious, albeit a little faggy. Sadly this political aspect ruined the music. Animals only suffers slightly since most of it is allegorical, and so it can be considered their last good album (Meddle obviously being their best album despite [nay, because of] Seamus). You can hear in the music of Animals that Gilmour* is still quite free to play in the style that suits him, it contains some of his best work. In the Wall, the playing is more constricted - the story and message is taking precedence, and so the instrumentation has to elicit a certain feeling - one which only Waters really felt. This is not necessarily a problem on Waters' part, since it was just for one album, and there is something to respect in how ambitious the project would have been. Unfortunately what it did was highlight the obvious - that pink floyd consisted of mediocre musicians who had some cool ideas in the 70s, but lacked any technical ability to expand further. The wall marked the end of PF, and as such it belongs in the trash alongside anything released by them afterwards.

>What do u mean by this?
He's not talking about microphone distance or any production stuff. Projecting your voice is basically making it louder while also making it fuller and more clear. Imagine the way you would talk if you had to give an hour long lecture to a room of 100 people with no microphone. You would be loud and clear but you wouldn't strain or scream because then your voice would blow out in a few minutes. To do that you would breathe and elevate in a certain way, and that's projection. That's something that's necessary to sing well. You've already got a naturally good voice so you're at an advantage. When you learn through time and muscle memory to be in tune, you will already have a great sound going, even without proper projection. But when you learn projection, you will have a greater range of expressions, tones, and dynamics that will give you the freedom to sing whatever you want. There are artists who used very little projection, like Nick Drake, and they had a certain sound because of it. Not that it's a bad thing, but it is more limited. Some people think limitations like that are good for creativity. But in my opinion, the kind of music you're doing has a wide range of possibilities, and it will be better for you if you can project. Unless you want to develop some kind of Johnny Cash sound, like Colter Wall is doing.

>>114015605
A compressor allows you to make the quiet parts of something louder, and the louder parts quiet - thereby "compressing" the final waveform.

Attack: How quickly the compressor starts to compress the audio. If it's very fast, the transients (very fast, sharp peaks) in things like snare drums and kick drums and vocals will be compressed [turned down] and potentially make the music sound less dynamic. Alternatively, if attack is very slow, the compressor won't be grabbing on to very much since it's just letting more loud sounds through.

Release: How quickly the compressor "lets go" of the signal it's compressing and starts looking for more audio to compress. The important thing to know about this is that if the release is very slow, the compressor is just turning down the audio and staying there. Fast release times tend to make things sound like they're "breathing" and are a major reason things might sound "compressed", whether that's good or bad is subjective.

Threshold: The audio level at which the compressor will actually kick in. Say you have an uncompressed snare drum that peaks around -12dB. If your compressor threshold is set anywhere above -12dB, the compressor will never engage because there's no audio it sees as loud enough to compress.

Ratio: The most convoluted setting to explain, probably the one that requires the most practical experience to understand. In my experience, ratios below 7:1 have essentially no impact on the audio unless you're trying to make reference-quality recordings. Basically, ratio is "how much" the compressor actually compresses the audio when it hits the threshold. The most useful model of compressor to demonstrate this is an 1176, or maybe a Distressor.

If you have access to it, the user interface for a Midas M32 or a Behringer X32 has a fantastic visual representation of a compressor that can help you understand these parameters.

How do I deal with setbacks, failures, delays, defeats, or other disasters? I actually have a fairly simple way of dealing with these situations, summed up in one word: “Good.” This is something that one of my direct subordinates, one of the guys I collabed with, a guy who became one of my best friends pointed out.
He would pull me aside with some major problem or issue that was going on, and he’d say, “Boss, we’ve got this thing, this situation, and it’s going terribly wrong.” I would look at him and say, “Good.” And finally, one day, he was telling me about something that was going off the rails, and as soon as he finished explaining it to me, he said, “I already know what you’re going to say.” And I asked, “What am I going to say?” And he said, “You’re going to say: ‘Good.’ ” He continued, “That’s what you always say. When something is wrong or going bad, you just look at me and say, ‘Good.’ ” And I said, “Well. I mean it. Because that is how I operate.” So I explained to him that when things are going bad, there’s going to be some good that will come from it.
Oh, the commission got canceled? Good… We can focus on another one.
Didn’t get the new modular gear we wanted? Good… We can keep it simple.
Didn’t get signed? Good… More time to get better.
Didn’t get new patreons? Good… We own more of the company.
Didn’t write the record you wanted? Good… Go out, gain more experience, and build a better resume.
Got tinnitus? Good… Needed a break from training.
Got kicked out from the basement? Good… It’s better to be kicked out in training than kicked out on tour.
Got outed as a /prod/ dweller? Good… We learned.
Unexpected problems? Good… We have to figure out a solution.
That’s it. When things are going bad: Don’t get all bummed out, don’t get started, don’t get frustrated. No. Just look at the issue and say: “Good.”

posts.com:
Cover as art : Nine Inch Nail's The Downward Spiral

Cover as an aesthetic : Joy Division's Unknown Pleasures.

Cover as a literal icon : Metallica's Ride the Lightning

Out of these, I've always preferred as an artist, what NIN did here in terms of the artwork for not only TDS, but the singles like March of the Pigs to tie it in, and even Further Down the Spiral.

Yet, Metallica's Ride the Lightning is obviously a more iconic and striking album cover, that clearly resonates more with audiences (children).

I think all great album covers are inherently simple which is why the TDS cover is nowhere near as iconic as the rest. Yet it is artistically I think much better, in terms of what it's trying to impart on the viewer. It takes more risks, it is less fashion. Aesthetic covers are sort of in the middle and appeal to the mu crowd but sort of alienates normies. Irony being Joy's cover has become an NPC icon. Ride the Lightning is the lowest in terms of artistic value but the standout in terms of punch. As an artist, I know in my heart that I should be pushing for a cover like that. But my heart says artwork. My brain trying to reason with me says meet in the middle, which I feel is even more cliche and pathetic than just making something pushy.

Those are all "art" tho. For me a good cover is simply something gives you some visual that improves your experience while listening to the music (and looks cool). Frankly, that's part of why Magma is by far my favorite zeuhl act, and not just because they were my first one. Haven't listened to Bondage Fruit yet, but I'm familiar with the other three bands you listed and like them a lot, but the chaos and energy they go for kinda misses out on that more otherworldy celestial vibe that Magma typically goes for. I think part of it is that they mostly hone in on the prog and rock elements, but most of Magma is very consciously informed by Carl Orff and John Coltrane, which is part of what makes zeuhl "Zeuhl" in the first place. I guess it's kinda ironic that the progenitors of this subgenre are actually the least accessible to some prog fans.
And just to warn you, their albums from 2004 and onwards after their reunion only get less "prog rock" sounding. The electric guitar becomes more of an afterthought, and a bigger emphasis is placed on the vocal harmonies.

>>114034688
Yes, Offering is great. While I definitely prefer Magma, I love that Vander's vocals play a larger role, and his drumming definitely sounds more like Rashied Ali or Elvin Jones in particular parts, which fits the mood so well. The more loose spiritual jazz structure is a nice take on the kind of music that inspired Zeuhl in the first place. The John/Alice Coltrane influence is even more apparent, and in such a beautiful and wholesome way. Outside of jazz, it's perhaps the closest a band has come to reaching that same sense of awe or beauty as A Love Supreme. While Part I/Part II is good, I definitely prefer the later albums. The song you linked is majestic.

Honestly I have a lot to say about this. In the 20th century the boomers had it so easy that it became "uncool" for an artist to do anything besides make art, because they knew full well they could just cut their hair, go to college, give some dude a firm handshake and become a homeowner before age 30 if the whole art thing didn't work out for them. But now that's starting to change, and things are going back to the way they used to be:

In the 1800's a lot of famous writers and painters held a sinecure for years, even decades before being able to make a living off their art. And yea, it's not as cool, but for hundreds of years it was a practical necessity to work as a postman or gov't employee or some menial desk job in order to be able to feed yourself and make art at the same time (ex. Herman Melville, Henri Rousseau, JK Huysmans). And now, for economic reasons this is going to *have* to come back

The next great musicians are almost certainly not going to be rich kids larping as Jim Morrison, they're going to be unassuming programmers etc who come out of the blue with things they've been working on for years. Because the financial situation is simply too dire for anyone to risk attempting to live off their art from the get go safe in the knowledge they can just pick up where they left off 10 years later if they fail. The other thing that's going to have to come back is old-fashioned patronage of the arts by really rich people. Bands like Can and Supertramp were only able to exist for this reason, and now the underground is almost completely destroyed this will be one of the only ways interesting music gets made

In general, the 3rd generation of K-pop is often considered to refer to groups that debuted in the late 1990s and early 2000s, while the 4th generation is often considered to refer to groups that debuted in the mid to late 2000s. However, these definitions can vary and there is not a strict dividing line between the two generations.

It is worth noting that the concept of "generations" in K-pop is a way of grouping artists and groups based on the time period in which they debuted, but it is not an official classification and there is not a fixed timeline for each generation.

>>114036228
When I was in high school my guitar rig was a Godin electric > ME20 > 20W Roland Cube

When I was in Uni my rig was an Epiphone Dot Deluxe > ME50 > 60W Kustom SS

When I graduated I went down the road of buying a “real” pedalboard and pedals and a tube amp.

I’m still playing the odd gig and sold all of the analog gear and got an modeller and a PA speaker for monitoring. I still have that 60w SS amp. Never been happier.

The Boss multi effects are very good for the price and give you lots of options. Definitely good bang for your buck while you are learning the instrument and developing. I don’t regret selling it but after buying all those pedals I realized I wasn’t missing out on much by just having the one ME50. Plus, you can add pedals to it if you want. They are built like tanks too.

If you are looking for a portable gigging solution the Helix Stomp is a cool unit with better digital effects.

Depends on where you are in your learning and what you require it for.
